# =============================================================================
# CORTEX :: Trivy image-scan allowlist (P14 / ADR-0058 D8 / issue #156)
# =============================================================================
# These HIGH/CRITICAL CVEs cannot be fixed inside the LOCKED Spring Boot 3.3.x
# stack (plan.md section 2: "Tech stack (LOCKED)"). Their only fixes ship in
# Spring Framework 6.2+ / Spring Security 6.5+ / Spring Boot 3.5+, which forces
# a Spring Boot 3.4+/3.5+ AND Spring Cloud 2023.0.4 -> 2024.0.x migration -- a
# separate, approval-gated architectural epic tracked in issue #156.
#
# Everything fixable WITHIN 3.3.x was burned down in P14 (PR #155): Spring Boot
# 3.3.6 -> 3.3.13, Spring AI 1.0.0 -> 1.0.8, Netty 4.1.135.Final, Tomcat
# 10.1.55, XStream 1.4.21, BouncyCastle 1.84, Jersey 3.1.10, plus apt-get
# upgrade on every runtime image. The Trivy gate is BLOCKING for every NEW
# fixable HIGH/CRITICAL; only the framework-locked residuals below are
# allowlisted, each with its fix-version and the migration it requires.
#
# Review trigger: revisit on the #156 Spring Boot 3.5+ migration, or if any CVE
# below gains a 3.3.x-compatible backport.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# spring-core: Spring Framework annotation-based access-control bypass.
# Installed 6.1.x (Boot 3.3.13) -> fix 6.2.11 (Spring Framework 6.2 = Boot 3.4+).
CVE-2025-41249

# spring-security-web (CRITICAL): security-policy bypass / authorization issue.
# Installed 6.3.x (Boot 3.3.13) -> fix 6.5.9 / 7.0.4 (Spring Security 6.5 = Boot 3.5+).
CVE-2026-22732

# spring-boot: framework-level hardening.
# Installed 3.3.13 -> fix 3.5.14 / 4.0.6 (Boot 3.5+).
CVE-2026-40973

# kafka-clients: information disclosure. Installed 3.7.2 (Boot 3.3.x-managed) ->
# fix 3.9.2. CANNOT bump within the locked stack: the embedded
# `spring-kafka-test` ZK broker (Spring Kafka 3.2.x, locked by Boot 3.3.x) hard-
# requires kafka-clients 3.7.x -- Kafka 3.8/3.9 removed `KafkaConfig.LogDirProp()`
# and `Utils.join(Collection, String)` that the 3.2.x broker still calls, so any
# bump breaks every `@EmbeddedKafka` test at context load. Fix requires the Boot
# 3.4+/Spring Kafka 3.3+ migration tracked in #156.
CVE-2026-35554

# spring-kafka: insecure deserialization hardening. Installed 3.2.10
# (Boot 3.3.13-managed) -> fix 3.3.16 / 4.0.6. CANNOT bump within the locked
# stack: Spring Kafka 3.3.16 is built on the Spring Framework 6.2.x ecosystem
# and brings kafka-clients 3.8.x; this is the same Boot 3.4+/Spring Kafka 3.3+
# migration tracked in #156.
CVE-2026-41731

# lz4-java: transitive of kafka-clients 3.7.2 (above). org.lz4:lz4-java 1.8.0 is
# what kafka-clients 3.7.2 pulls; the patched releases (1.8.1 for CVE-2025-12183,
# 1.10.1 for CVE-2025-66566) only ship under the `at.yawk.lz4` fork, so clearing
# them means an exclude-and-swap of a transitive of the locked kafka-clients.
# Part of the same kafka-clients 3.7.2 locked subtree; cleared by the Spring
# Kafka 3.3+ migration (#156), which ships a newer kafka-clients + lz4-java.
CVE-2025-12183
CVE-2025-66566
